    {
        "content": "<p>I'd also be in favor of convenient syntax for binding an optional expected type! I frequently find myself turning to <code>@[term_elab]</code> to access it.</p>\n<p>To iterate on the above suggestions, I'd suggest the similar variant <code>&lt;= (ty)?</code> specifically for its similarity to existing optional <code>Syntax</code> syntax, and the \"danger\" of having <code>ty ?</code> mean something different from <code>ty?</code> (which seems easy to typo).</p>\n<p>In general I think the syntax should preferably be (1) close to the existing syntax and (2) backwards-compatible! :)</p>",
        "id": 454405446,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Murrills",
        "timestamp": 1722045871
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Something I've been thinking about recently is that the expected type could be part of the reader state, letting you write <code>← getExpectedType?</code> without needing to find a backwards-compatible syntax</p>",
        "id": 454406328,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1722046626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That would be great! I remember checking to see if it was already part of the state at one point, so maybe that's one small data point in favor of it \"feeling natural\"</p>",
